<body>

    <header>
        <div class="container">
            <h1>The American Revolution</h1>
            <p>1775–1783: The Fight for Independence</p>
        </div>
    </header>

    <main class="container">

        <section class="hero">
            <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1b/Declaration_of_Independence_%281819%29_by_John_Trumbull.jpg/300px-Declaration_of_Independence_%281819%29_by_John_Trumbull.jpg" alt="Declaration of Independence">
            <div class="hero-text">
                <h2>The Birth of a Nation</h2>
                <p>The American Revolution was an ideological and political upheaval that occurred between 1765 and 1791, primarily involving the thirteen American colonies' fight against Great Britain's authority. It led to the creation of the United States as an independent nation through the Declaration of Independence in 1776 and the Treaty of Paris in 1783.</p>
                <a href="#timeline" class="btn">Explore the Timeline</a>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="causes">
            <h2>Causes of the Revolution</h2>
            <div class="grid">
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Taxation Without Representation</h3>
                    <p>Acts like the Stamp Act (1765) and Townshend Acts (1767) imposed taxes on the colonies without their consent, sparking protests such as the Boston Tea Party (1773).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>British Policies Post-French & Indian War</h3>
                    <p>The end of the Seven Years' War in 1763 left Britain in debt, leading to stricter control over the colonies via the Proclamation of 1763 and Quartering Act (1765).</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Enlightenment Ideas</h3>
                    <p>Influenced by thinkers like John Locke, colonists demanded natural rights, self-government, and resistance to tyranny, fueling the push for independence.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="timeline">
            <h2>Key Events Timeline</h2>
            <div class="timeline">
                <div class="timeline-item left">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">April 19, 1775</span>
                        <h3>Battles of Lexington and Concord</h3>
                        <p>The "shot heard 'round the world" – First military engagements of the Revolution, where colonial minutemen clashed with British troops.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item right">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">June 17, 1775</span>
                        <h3>Battle of Bunker Hill</h3>
                        <p>Colonists defended Breed's Hill against British forces, proving they could stand against regular troops despite heavy losses.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item left">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">July 4, 1776</span>
                        <h3>Declaration of Independence</h3>
                        <p>Adopted by the Continental Congress, drafted primarily by Thomas Jefferson, proclaiming the colonies' separation from Britain.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item right">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">December 25–26, 1776</span>
                        <h3>Washington Crosses the Delaware</h3>
                        <p>George Washington's surprise attack on Hessian forces at Trenton boosted Patriot morale after a string of defeats.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item left">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">October 17, 1777</span>
                        <h3>Battle of Saratoga</h3>
                        <p>A turning point; American victory convinced France to ally with the colonies, bringing crucial support.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item right">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">February 6, 1778</span>
                        <h3>Treaty of Alliance with France</h3>
                        <p>France recognized U.S. independence and provided military aid, shifting the war's balance.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item left">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">October 19, 1781</span>
                        <h3>Siege of Yorktown</h3>
                        <p>Combined American and French forces trapped British General Cornwallis, leading to his surrender and the war's effective end.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="timeline-item right">
                    <div class="timeline-content">
                        <span class="date">September 3, 1783</span>
                        <h3>Treaty of Paris</h3>
                        <p>Britain formally recognized U.S. independence, ending the Revolutionary War.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="figures">
            <h2>Major Figures</h2>
            <div class="grid">
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>George Washington</h3>
                    <p>Commander-in-Chief of the Continental Army; his leadership and resilience were pivotal to victory.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Thomas Jefferson</h3>
                    <p>Principal author of the Declaration of Independence; third U.S. President.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>Benjamin Franklin</h3>
                    <p>Diplomat who secured French alliance; inventor, writer, and Founding Father.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="card">
                    <h3>King George III</h3>
                    <p>British monarch whose policies, like taxation acts, fueled colonial resentment.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>

        <section id="legacy">
            <h2>Legacy & Impact</h2>
            <p style="text-align:center; font-size:1.1rem;">The Revolution inspired global movements for liberty and democracy, establishing principles of republican government and individual rights. It also highlighted tensions over slavery and Native American lands, shaping future U.S. challenges.</p>
        </section>

